ce:section.ce:para:
The immobilization of nanoparticles is crucial for developing immunosensors. It is well known that carbon nanomaterials exhibit unique properties (excellent conductivity and catalytic properties), which allow us to use them as “electronic wires” to create the redox centers in biomolecules and electrode surfaces. For example, Luo et al. (2014) developed a novel sandwich-type immunoassay approach for the detection of squamous cell carcinoma antigen using Fe3O4 NPs and CdTe–CDs as substrates. The sensing mechanism is based on the ECL resonance energy transfer between magnetic-force-controlled carbon paste electrode and CdTe–CD-labeled secondary antibody. The authors studied various influencing parameters (the effects of buffers, pH values, and concentrations of H2O2) on ECL intensity. They observed that the maximum ECL intensity was obtained in 2×10−4
                  mol/l H2O2 at pH 8.0, offering a detection limit of 6.3fg/ml. Similarly, Yang’s group developed an eco-friendly CD-based fluorescence immunoassay approach for the simple and rapid detection of human immunoglobulin G (IgG, antigen) (Li et al., 2014). To obtain CD-labeled goat antihuman IgG (gIgG antibody), the authors functionalized CDs with gIgG antibody by carbodiimide-mediated amidation reaction between 1-ethyl-3-(3-dimethylaminopropyl) carbodiimide hydrochloride (EDC) and N-hydroxysuccinimide (NHS) and the obtained CD–gIgG conjugate was treated with a limited amount of human IgG. The CD-conjugated platform acts as a highly ordered immunosensor for the detection of human IgG through an immunocomplex between the surfaces of CD-conjugates and target analyte, and offers a detection limit of 0.01μg/ml. This method was successfully applied to detect IgG in human serum. Recently, Chen’s and Wang’s groups developed a facile method for the preparation of Ag NPs using CDs as a reducing agent (Shen et al., 2014). Interestingly, the excessive CDs are consumed by free Ag+ in the solution by binding Ag+ with functional groups on CD surfaces, which results inhibiting the growth of Ag NPs. The authors observed that biothiols can coordinate with Ag+ through mercapto groups, and afterward, Ag+–biothiol complex gradually releases free Ag+ to ensure its reduction by CDs, facilitating the growth of Ag NPs on the surface of CDs. The CD-coated Ag NPs were used as a colorimetric probe for facile and sensitive detection of three biothiols including cysteine (Cys), homocysteine (Hcy), and glutathione (GSH) in biological fluids. Chang’s group prepared CDs capped with reduced graphene oxide (RGO) using catechin as a reducing agent and carbon source, and used as fluorescent probes for detection of glucose (Yeh et al., 2013) and acetylcholine (ACh) (Wang et al., 2013a). Furthermore, CD–RGO nanomaterials exhibit unique optical properties such as excitation- wavelength-dependence PL characteristics, which allow us to use them as unique optical discriminative probes for the detection of H2O2 and glucose through a “turn-on” PL mechanism (Yeh et al., 2013). The authors successfully applied to detect and quantify glucose in serum and saliva samples. The same authors also described the use of CD–RGO as a probe for detection of ACh (Wang et al., 2013a). This approach is based on the conversion of Ach to choline in the presence of acetylcholinesterase (AChE), yielding betaine and H2O2 products by choline oxidase (ChOx) which facilitates the generation of reactive oxygen species. As a result, the PL intensity of CD–RGO is inversely proportional to the concentration of ACh (0.05−10nM), and provides LOD of 30pM for ACh in plasma samples (Figure 11.2
                  ). The same group prepared highly hydrophilic photoluminescent RGO sheets and then decorated with CD–methylene blue (MB) for the sensitive detection of DNA (Wang et al., 2014a,b). The authors observed that the MB effectively quenched the PL intensity of CD–RGO, however it was restored in the presence of target DNA, which indicates that this approach was very selective for the detection of target DNA. MB molecules are released from the surfaces of CD–RGO due to the interaction of MB with ds-DNA, resulting in restoration of the PL intensity (Figure 11.3a
                  ). The fluorescence images of DNA-P/CD–RGO–MB in the absence and presence of DNA-T1, DNA-T2, or DNA-T3 are shown in Figure 11.3b. This method was successfully applied to detect target DNA with high selectivity and sensitivity, offering its potential for multiple analyses of DNA targets.

Monodisperse highly fluorescent CDs have been synthesized at gram scale with a high yield (41.8%) by carbonization of sucrose with oil acid in one step (Chen et al., 2013). These authors demonstrated their potential applications in bioimaging of 16HBE cells. Cellular uptake of the CDs can be observed at an excitation wavelength 488nm laser. The photoluminescent spots were observed only in the cytoplasmic area of the cell, whereas the PL intensity of the nucleus at the central region is very weak, indicating that the CDs easily penetrated into the cell but did not enter the nuclei, which avoids genetic disruption. Wu’s group developed CD-based FRET with organic dye-based ratiometric sensor for sensing and imaging of H2S in biological fluids and in living cells (Yu et al., 2013). Strongly green fluorescent graphene CDs were prepared in a one-step solvothermal method using graphene oxide as precursor (Zhu et al., 2011). The prepared carbon-based material possessed low cytotoxicity and culture medium (104 cells) did not weaken the cell activity even at 400µg. It was noticed that the bright green area was observed inside the cells, which confirms the translocation of carbon nanomaterials through the cell membrane. Hahn’s team demonstrated the application of polyethylene glycol (PEG) diamine-capped CDs for real-time bioimaging of target-specific delivery of hyaluronic acid (HA) derivatives (Hahn et al., 2012). The authors carried out in vitro bioimaging of target-specific intracellular delivery of the HA−CD conjugates by HA receptor-mediated endocytosis. It was noticed that the cellular uptake of HA−CD conjugates was drastically reduced due to the competitive binding of HA to the receptors (Figure 11.6a
                  ). Similarly, the cellular uptake of CDs after conjugation to HA was significantly reduced in HEK293 cells without HA receptors (Figure 11.6b). This approach can be useful for the treatment of liver diseases and for various bioimaging applications. Jana’s group developed a chemical method for synthesis of highly fluorescent CDs used as cell-imaging probes (Bhunia et al., 2013). To prove the functionalized CDs as fluorescent probes, the authors investigated their applications in cell imaging (Figure 11.7
                  ). The functionalized CDs successfully increased cell labeling and uptake. Tan’s group prepared multicolor CDs by chemical nitric acid oxidation using the reproducible plant soot as a raw material (Tan et al., 2013). The authors investigated their potential applications for imaging of Chinese Hamster Ovary (CHO) cells and guppy fish imaging and showed enhanced luminescence as compared with its control with a signal-to-noise (S/N) ratio. The same group prepared high PL CDs using commercial Nescafe instant coffee as the carbon source (Jiang et al., 2014). To explore their potential use in cell imaging, the authors performed an in vitro cellular uptake experiment of CDs in human hepatocellular carcinoma cells (Figure 11.8a
                  ). As a result, the hepatocellular carcinoma cells incubated with CDs become bright as compared with the control cells without adding the CDs. These results indicated that CDs were successfully applied to observe multiple color emission in cells. In order to investigate its practical applications, CDs were applied as probes to observe PL of a CD–food mixture (Figure 11.8b). These results demonstrated that the guppy fish fed with the CD–food mixture clearly showed enhanced PL, which was much higher than that of the control fish (Figure 11.8c). The authors found that the CDs showed low biotoxicity, which confirms that CDs are good candidates for in vivo small animal imaging.
